{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01SyPEtbdHfTftRwuhzHP8Hv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The WiredTiger runtime config is empty (\"\") which means it's using the default. The default journal compressor for MongoDB 6.0 is snappy.\n\nNow I need to:\n1. Apply runtime changes (logLevel to 2, slowms to 400) to ALL members\n2. Change WiredTiger journal compression to zlib\n\nFor the journal compression, I have two options:\n1. Set `wiredTigerEngineRuntimeConfig` with `journal=(compressor=zlib)` at runtime (affects current session)\n2. Update the StatefulSet command to persist across restarts, then do a rolling restart\n3. Update the StatefulSet to add the `--wiredTigerJournalCompressor zlib` flag and apply runtime changes to all current members, then perform a rolling restart so each pod picks up the new configuration\n\nThe key consideration is whether a rolling restart will maintain data availability during the process.\n\nFor a 5-member replica set, I can safely restart one member at a time. The StatefulSet's rolling update strategy will restart pods from the highest ordinal down to the primary, which means the majority stays up throughout. But I also need to make sure the logLevel and slowms changes are applied before the rolling restart begins.\n\nThe tricky part is persistence - logLevel changes via `setParameter` don't survive restarts, and neither do profiling threshold changes set through `db.setProfilingLevel()`. I need to figure out how to make these configuration changes stick across the restart cycle.\n\nThe solution is to bake these settings into the StatefulSet command itself, so they're applied at startup. I'll add the persistent parameters directly to the mongod command line, then apply runtime changes to the current members for immediate effect. When the StatefulSet rolls out the updated configuration, the new settings will be applied as each pod restarts. Setting the WiredTiger journal compressor at runtime through `wiredTigerEngineRuntimeConfig` should work since MongoDB exposes WiredTiger's reconfigure API, and the journal compressor is a runtime-reconfigurable setting. So I'll proceed with applying all three runtime changes before the rolling restart to minimize downtime. I can set the slowms threshold either at startup via command-line flags or at runtime through the admin command, where `profile: 0` disables profiling while updating the threshold. For the StatefulSet, I'll patch it to include the persistent flags for log level, slow operation threshold, and journal compression, which will trigger a rolling restart. The runtime changes take effect immediately, while the restart ensures the configuration persists across pod restarts.\n\nDuring the rolling restart, Kubernetes will restart pods from highest to lowest ordinal, so the secondaries go down first (mongodb-replica-4 through mongodb-replica-1) while the primary (mongodb-replica-0) restarts last. Since we have 5 members and only need 3 for quorum, we maintain majority availability throughout—at most one pod is down at any time. and so on. This should be safe for a 5-member replica set since we maintain quorum throughout.\n\nWhen the primary gets restarted, the replica set will briefly need to elect a new leader, which typically takes a few seconds. I'm weighing whether to explicitly step down the primary beforehand using `rs.stepDown()` or just let the StatefulSet rolling update handle it naturally. The standard MongoDB upgrade procedure recommends stepping down first, but since the StatefulSet will manage the restart sequentially anyway, I could either skip the manual step-down or do it preemptively before patching.\n\nGiven the requirement that data stays available, I'll go with the straightforward approach: apply the runtime parameter changes to all members immediately, patch the StatefulSet with the persistent settings, then monitor the rolling update until all pods are healthy. For the implementation, I need to connect to each replica member individually and apply `setParameter` commands, which should work on secondaries even though they can't handle data-modifying admin commands. I need to verify whether the WiredTiger runtime config change can be applied on secondaries and test it on a single node first before rolling it out across the cluster.\n\nLooking at the WiredTiger documentation, I see that the reconfigure API supports various runtime changes like cache and eviction settings, but journal compressor changes are actually a creation-time setting that can't be modified at runtime. So I'll need to update the StatefulSet with the `--wiredTigerJournalCompressor zlib` flag and perform a rolling restart of all pods to apply that change, while the logLevel and slowms adjustments can be applied immediately to all members.\n\nSince journal files are transient and get replayed and rotated, there shouldn't be compatibility issues when switching the compressor during the rolling update. I also need to check the StatefulSet configuration more carefully—it currently has the basic mongod command with replSet and bind_ip_all flags, but I'm not seeing the `--auth` or `--keyFile` parameters even though there's a mongo-keyfile secret referenced elsewhere. I need to look back at the full StatefulSet YAML to see if there are initContainers or volume mounts I missed, since we're able to authenticate but there's no `--keyFile` or `--auth` flag in the command. Maybe the keyfile is mounted somewhere else or auth was configured through a different mechanism like a config file on disk.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2097,"cache_read_input_tokens":32962,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2097},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_managemen